Subject: non-membrane-bounded organelle
Value: Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function, not bounded by a lipid bilayer membrane. Includes ribosomes, the cytoskeleton and chromosomes.

Subject: ribosome
Value: Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function, not bounded by a lipid bilayer membrane. Includes ribosomes, the cytoskeleton and chromosomes.

Subject: endoplasmic reticulum
Value: Network of interconnected, flattened, and/or tubular membrane, known as cisternae. This membrane is contiguous with the outer nuclear membrane. The endoplasmic reticulum is involved in both protein and lipid synthesis.

Subject: rough endoplasmic reticulum
Value: Network of interconnected, flattened, and/or tubular membrane, known as cisternae. This membrane is contiguous with the outer nuclear membrane. The endoplasmic reticulum is involved in both protein and lipid synthesis.

Subject: presynaptic vesicle
Value: A secretory organelle, typically 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals; accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.

Subject: synaptic vesicle
Value: A secretory organelle, typically 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals; accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.

Subject: wedge amputation
Value: A piece of tissue removed from the lateral margin at any given point that extendes interiorly to more medial structures.

Subject: wedge fragment
Value: A piece of tissue removed from the lateral margin at any given point that extendes interiorly to more medial structures.

Subject: autonomic neuron
Value: A neruon whose cell body is within an autonomic ganglion.

Subject: enteric neuron
Value: A neruon whose cell body is within an autonomic ganglion.

Subject: cell-cell junction
Value: A cell junction that forms a connection between two or more cells in a multicellular organism; excludes direct cytoplasmic junctions such as ring canals.

Subject: intercellular junction
Value: A cell junction that forms a connection between two or more cells in a multicellular organism; excludes direct cytoplasmic junctions such as ring canals.

Subject: incision
Value: A breach of the epidermis made with a defined edge or point.

Subject: point incision
Value: A breach of the epidermis made with a defined edge or point.

pharynx progenitor cell

Subject: spermatogonial stem cell
Value: gh4+, nanos+ cells residing at the testis periphery that self-renew and give rise to differentiating daughters that will ultimately produce haploid sperm.

Subject: germ cell
Value: 1. A gamete (as an egg or sperm cell) or one of its antecedent cells. 2. A mature male or female germ cell usually possessing a haploid chromosome set and capable of initiating formation of a new diploid individual by fusion with a gamete of the opposite sex.

Subject: brain commissure
Value: any of the nerve fiber tracts that span the longitudinal fissure between the cerebral and/or cerebellar hemispheres of the brain
